{"title_page": "2019\u201320 Atlanta SC season", "text_new": "{{short description|The club's inaugural season in the National Independent Soccer Association}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n| club                 = [[Atlanta SC]]\n| owner                = \n| chrtitle             = President\n| chairman             = Phoday Dolleh\n| manager              = Roberto Neves\n| mgrtitle             = Head coach\n| American             = true\n| league             = [[National Independent Soccer Association|NISA]]\n| league result      = '''[[2019\u201320 NISA season#Fall season|Fall]]''', East Coast Conf.: 3rd<br>'''[[2019\u201320 NISA season#Spring season|Spring]]''': N/A\n| cup1               = Playoffs\n| cup1 result        = '''[[2019\u201320 NISA season#Playoffs|Fall]]''': DNQ<br>'''[[2019\u201320 NISA season#Spring season|Spring]]''': N/A\n| league topscorer     = [[Nazeem Bartman]] (3)\n| season topscorer     = [[Nazeem Bartman]] (3)\n| highest attendance   = 252<br>{{nowrap|<small>(October 12 vs. [[Miami FC]])</small>}}\n| lowest attendance    = 112<br>{{nowrap|<small>(September 14 vs. [[Stumptown Athletic]])</small>}}\n| average attendance   = {{formatnum:{{#expr: ((+112 +252)/2) round 0}}}}\n| largest win          = N/A\n| largest loss         = 1\u20133<br><small>(September 14 vs. [[Stumptown Athletic]])</small>\n| season               = [[2019\u201320 NISA season|2019\u201320 NISA]]\n| stadium              = [[St. Francis Schools (Alpharetta, Georgia)|St. Francis High School]] (2 games)<br>[[Alpharetta, Georgia|Alpharetta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]]<br>[[Life University|Lupo Family Stadium]] (1 game)<br>[[Marietta, Georgia]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|GA]]\n| prevseason           = [[2019 NPSL season|2019]]\n| nextseason           =\n}}\nThe 2019\u201320 [[Atlanta SC]] season was the club's first season playing professionally and its first in the [[National Independent Soccer Association]] (NISA), a newly established [[United States soccer league system|third division soccer league in the United States]].\n\n== Overview ==\nOn November 20, 2018, the National Independent Soccer Association announced that a team from Atlanta would begin play in its inaugural season in fall 2019..<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nisaofficial.com/news/2018/11/20/new-professional-soccer-club-coming-to-atlanta|title=NEW PROFESSIONAL SOCCER CLUB COMING TO ATLANTA|website=nisaofficial.com|publisher=National Independent Soccer Association|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.insideworldfootball.com/2018/11/21/nisa-unveils-atlanta-4th-team-us-3rd-tier-will-take-brakes-off-transfer-business/|title=NISA unveils Atlanta as 4th team in US 3rd tier that will take the brakes off transfer business|date=2018-11-21|website=Inside World Football|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref> In late 2019, following the end of the [[2019 NPSL season|National Premier Soccer League season]] Atlanta SC announced it would be joining NISA.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.atlsoccerclub.com/post/professional-soccer-club-atlanta-sc-announces-new-league-membership-with-nisa|title=Professional Soccer Club Atlanta SC Announces New League|last=|first=|date=|website=Atlanta Soccer Club|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 12, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.socceramerica.com/publications/article/83089/nisa-will-launch-with-abbreviated-schedule.html|title=NISA will launch with abbreviated schedule|website=www.socceramerica.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/miami-fc-makes-surprise-move-031026598.html|title=Miami FC makes surprise move to United Soccer League|website=sports.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-12}}</ref>\n\nOn January 8, the full list of teams taking part in the 2020 [[U.S. Open Cup]] was announced including eight from the [[National Independent Soccer Association]]. Since Atlanta SC was not listed among these teams, and all professional clubs within the United States are required to take part in the tournament, this signaled that the club will not take part in professional play in the Spring 2020 season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ussoccer.com/stories/2020/01/record-setting-100-teams-confirmed-for-2020-lamar-hunt-us-open-cup|title=RECORD-SETTING 100 TEAMS CONFIRMED FOR 2020 LAMAR HUNT U.S. OPEN CUP, 107TH EDITION OF U.S. SOCCER\u2019S NATIONAL CHAMPIONSHIP|website=ussoccer.com|publisher=U.S. Soccer|accessdate=8 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Roster ==\n\n=== Players ===\n{{updated|December 27, 2019|}}<ref>{{cite web |title=Atlanta SC Roster |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191227084747/https://www.atlsoccerclub.com/roster |website=Atlanta Soccer Club |publisher=Wayback Machine |accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#008000; color:#ff992d; border:2px solid #000000;\" scope=\"col\"|No.\n! style=\"background:#008000; color:#ff992d; border:2px solid #000000;\" scope=\"col\"|Position\n! style=\"background:#008000; color:#ff992d; border:2px solid #000000;\" scope=\"col\"|Player\n! style=\"background:#008000; color:#ff992d; border:2px solid #000000;\" scope=\"col\"|Nation\n|-\n{{Fs player2 sort|no=1|nat=SCO|pos=GK|first=Jordan|last=Bell|dab=Jordan Bell (footballer)}}\n{{Fs player2 sort|no=3|nat=ESP|pos=DF|first=Manu|last=Moreno}}\n{{Fs player2 sort|no=4|nat=TOG|pos=DF|first=Ramzi|last=Toure}}\n{{Fs player2 sort|no=5|nat=SLE|pos=DF|first=Sheriff|last=Suma}}\n{{Fs player2 sort|no=6|nat=LBR|pos=DF|first=Ricardo|last=George}}\n{{Fs player2 sort|no=7|nat=SAF|pos=FW|first=Nazeem|last=Bartman}}\n{{Fs player2 sort|no=8|nat=FRA|pos=MF|first=Alexandre|last=Frank}}\n{{Fs player2 sort|no=9|nat=CMR|pos=FW|first=William|last=Eyang}}\n{{Fs player2 sort|no=10|nat=LBR|pos=FW|first=Prince|last=Saydee}}\n{{Fs player2 sort|no=11|nat=LBR|pos=FW|first=Molley|last=Karpeh, Jr.}}\n{{Fs player2 sort|no=12|nat=GHA|pos=FW|first=Derrick|last=Boateng}}\n{{Fs player2