nal links ==\n\n* {{Official website|https://www.atlsoccerclub.com/}}\n\n{{National Independent Soccer Association}}\n{{2019\u201320 National Independent Soccer Association season by team}}\n{{2019 in American soccer}}\n\n[[Category:American soccer clubs 2019 season]]\n[[Category:2019 in sports in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n", "name_user": "ColeTrain4EVER", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019%E2%80%9320_Atlanta_SC_season"}
{"title_page": "William Ralph Turner", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=October 2010}}\n\n'''William Ralph Turner''' (30 April 1920 - 10 July 2013) <ref>{{cite news|author=Paul Barker |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/william-turner-painter-who-emerged-from-lowrys-shadow-when-he-was-in-his-eighties-8708172.html |title=William Turner: Painter who emerged from Lowry\u2019s shadow when he was in his eighties - Obituaries - News |publisher=The Independent |date= 14 July 2013|accessdate=2013-07-17 |location=London}}</ref> was a [[Painting|painter]] from [[Manchester]].\n\nWilliam Ralph Turner was born in [[Chorlton-on-Medlock]], [[Manchester]] in 1920. A largely self taught painter and teacher,<ref>The Northern School: A Reappraisal</ref> he has become known as one of the last authentic [[Northern England|Northern English]] industrial artists. Lowry was to visit Turner's exhibitions at the Tib Lane gallery in the 1950s and 60s,<ref>A Northern School, Peter Davies</ref> and the influence of [[L.S. Lowry]] can be seen in Turner's work.\n\nFor about 60 years Turner painted the North West and surrounding areas, often from memories and images obtained while indulging his passion for cycling long distances. A prolific painter, he painted thousands of pictures, including several hundred that featured the [[Stockport Viaduct]]. He was commissioned by Peter Burdett (of The Pitcairn Gallery) in the 1970s to paint Lyon in France and was represented by The Pitcairn until 1985 when the then owner, Wendy Levy, sold the gallery. In the 1980s he had exhibitions in Windsor and Eton and self organised shows in and around the Cheshire area including at Adlington Hall <ref> The Northern School: A Reappraisal</ref> and in 1989 he was featured in a major book about Northern Artists<ref>A Northern School</ref> by the artist and critic Peter Davies. Turner was \"re-discovered\" by David Gunning, an art dealer from Todmorden, in 2000, when Turner was 80.\n\n[[Parkinson's disease]] eventually forced Turner to stop painting. In 2005, he was given a retrospective at [[Gallery Oldham]] with an accompanying book.<ref>William Turner, An English Expressionist</ref> An exhibition of Turner's work took place at Clark Art in Hale, Cheshire, in 2010.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* A Northern School, Lancashire Artists of the 20th Century 1989, Peter Davies, {{ISBN|978-0948265730}}\n* William Ralph Turner by Stuart Archer & Bill Clark\n* ''William Turner, An English Expressionist'', 2005, Paul Barker and Stephen Whittle, {{ISBN|978-0955038501}}\n* William Ralph Turner in \"''The Northern School: A Reappraisal''\", 2015, Martin Regan, {{ISBN|978-1527203204}} \n* William Ralph Turner, Compelling Visions by Dr Paul Morgan\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.todmordenfineart.co.uk/tm/WilliamRT.eb\n* http://www.clark-art.co.uk\n* Ralph Turner's work at [http://www.gateway-gallery.co.uk/artists/william-ralph-turner/ Gateway Gallery] \n* Ralph Turner's work at [https://artuk.org/discover/artists/turner-william-ralph-19202013 ArtUK]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turner, William}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:People from Chorlton-on-Medlock]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=October 2010}}\n\n'''William Ralph Turner''' (20 April 1920 - 10 July 2013) <ref>{{cite news|author=Paul Barker |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/william-turner-painter-who-emerged-from-lowrys-shadow-when-he-was-in-his-eighties-8708172.html |title=William Turner: Painter who emerged from Lowry\u2019s shadow when he was in his eighties - Obituaries - News |publisher=The Independent |date= 14 July 2013|accessdate=2013-07-17 |location=London}}</ref> was a [[Painting|painter]] from [[Manchester]].\n\nWilliam Ralph Turner was born in [[Chorlton-on-Medlock]], [[Manchester]] in 1920. A largely self taught painter and teacher,<ref>The Northern School: A Reappraisal</ref> he has become known as one of the last authentic [[Northern England|Northern English]] industrial artists. Lowry was to visit Turner's exhibitions at the Tib Lane gallery in the 1950s and 60s,<ref>A Northern School, Peter Davies</ref> and the influence of [[L.S. Lowry]] can be seen in Turner's work.\n\nFor about 60 years Turner painted the North West and surrounding areas, often from memories and images obtained while indulging his passion for cycling long distances. A prolific painter, he painted thousands of pictures, including several hundred that featured the [[Stockport Viaduct]]. He was commissioned by Peter Burdett (of The Pitcairn Gallery) in the 1970s to paint Lyon in France and was represented by The Pitcairn until 1985 when the then owner, Wendy Levy, sold the gallery. In the 1980s he had exhibitions in Windsor and Eton and self organised shows in and around the Cheshire area including at Adlington Hall <ref> The Northern School: A Reappraisal</ref> and in 1989 he was featured in a major book about Northern Artists<ref>A Northern School</ref> by the artist and critic Peter Davies. Turner was \"re-discovered\" by David Gunning, an art dealer from Todmorden, in 2000, when Turner was 80.\n\n[[Parkinson's disease]] eventually forced Turner to stop painting. In 2005, he was given a retrospective at [[Gallery Oldham]] with an accompanying book.<ref>William Turner, An English Expressionist</ref> An exhibition of Turner's work took place at Clark Art in Hale, Cheshire, in 2010.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* A Northern School, Lancashire Artists of the 20th Century 1989, Peter Davies, {{ISBN|978-0948265730}}\n* William Ralph Turner by Stuart Archer & Bill Clark\n* ''William Turner, An English Expressionist'', 2005, Paul Barker and Stephen Whittle, {{ISBN|978-0955038501}}\n* William Ralph Turner in \"''The Northern School: A Reappraisal''\", 2015, Martin Regan, {{ISBN|978-1527203204}} \n* William Ralph Turner, Compelling Visions by Dr Paul Morgan\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.todmordenfineart.co.uk/tm/WilliamRT.eb\n* http://www.clark-art.co.uk\n* Ralph Turner's work at [http://www.gateway-gallery.co.uk/artists/william-ralph-turner/ Gateway Gallery] \n* Ralph Turner's work at [https://artuk.org/discover/artists/turner-william-ralph-19202013 ArtUK]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Turner, William}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2013 deaths]]\n[[Category:Modern painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century English painters]]\n[[Category:People from Chorlton-on-Medlock]]\n", "name_user": "Billclark007", "label": "safe", "comment": "entered correct date of birth", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Ralph_Turner"}
{"title_page": "Marie Hassenpflug", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Marie Hassenpflug\n| image            = Marie Hassenpflug Bildnis.jpg\n| imagesize        = \n| caption          = Marie Hassenpflug, 1812\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = December 27, 1788\n| birth_place      = Altenha\u00dflau, Germany\n| death_date       = November 21, 1856\n| death_place      = [[Kassel, Germany]]\n| nationality      = \n| spouse           = Friedrich von Dalwigk zu Schauenburg\n| field            = [[Writer]]\n}}\n'''Marie Magdalene Elisabeth Hassenpflug''' (born December 27, 1788 in [[Altenha\u00dflau, Germany,]] \u2020 November 21, 1856 in [[Kassel]]), married ''to Dalwigk von Schaumburg'', was an important source of fairy tales for the collection of children's and household tales by the [[Brothers Grimm]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Boehncke, Heiner,|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/856902587|title=Marie Hassenpflug : eine M\u00e4rchenerz\u00e4hlerin der Br\u00fcder Grimm|others=Schmidt, Phoebe Alexa,|isbn=978-3-8053-4536-1|location=Darmstadt|oclc=856902587}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Boehncke|first=Heiner|url=https://searchworks.stanford.edu/view/10238940|title=Marie Hassenpflug : eine M\u00e4rchenerz\u00e4hlerin der Br\u00fcder Grimm /|date=c2013.|publisher=Philipp von Zabern,|isbn=978-3-8053-4536-1|location=Darmstadt :}}</ref> She is most well known for her version of [[Little Red Riding Hood]], [[Sleeping Beauty]], and [[Snow White]]. \n\n== Life ==\nMarie was the daughter of Johannes Hassenpflug (1755-1834) and Marie Magdalena Dresen (born September 28, 1767 in [[Hanau]], \u2020 December 19, 1840 in [[Kassel]]), who came from a Huguenot emigrant family based in Hanau, and was one sister of the Kurhessian Minister of the Interior and Justice Ludwig Hassenpflug (1794-1862). When her father, Johannes Hassenpflug, became the school hotspot of Hanau Neustadt in 1789, the family moved into an apartment in \"Haus Amsterdam\", later \"Haus Lossow\", a representative half-timbered building on the southwest corner of the market square. The family was friends with the Grimm family, whose father, Philipp Wilhelm Grimm, was the clerk of the city and the B\u00fcchertal office. In 1799 the Hassenpflug family moved to Kassel, where Johannes Hassenpflug had moved to the financial administration of the Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fr.de/rhein-main/main-kinzig-kreis/spd-org26325/marie-hassenpflug-kind-lebte-11651780.html|title=Wo Marie Hassenpflug als Kind lebte|date=2013-09-06|website=https://www.fr.de|language=de|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/681999404|title=Fairy tales and society : illusion, allusion, and paradigm|date=1986|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|others=Bottigheimer, Ruth B.,|isbn=978-0-8122-0150-5|location=Philadelphia|oclc=681999404}}</ref>\n\nMarie Hassenpflug married Friedrich von Dalwigk zu Schauenburg on August 21, 1814, who was stationed in Hanau as captain of the ''Kurprinz regiment'' . In the following period she lived on her husband's farm in Hoof (today part of [[Schauenburg]]) and in Hanau. Her son, Ludwig Alexander, was born here on January 24, 1817.\n\nFrom 1819 to 1824 she had a job as [[court lady]] of the Duchess Marie Friederike von Anhalt-Bernburg, a daughter of the landgrave and later Elector Wilhelm IX./I. from Hessen-Kassel. Her husband was also the Duchess' [[Chamberlain (office)|chamberlain]]. During this time they lived in the Hanau City Palace. \n\n== Literary Significance ==\nMarie Hassenpflug wrote a series of fairy tales that the [[Brothers Grimm|Grimm brothers]] portray in the ''children's and house fairy tales'' (KHM) they wrote: ''Little Brother and Sister'' (KHM 11), ''Little Red Riding Hood'' (KHM 26), ''The Girl Without Hands'' (KHM 31), ''The robber groom'' (KHM 40), ''Daumerling's wanderings'' (KHM 45), ''Sleeping Beauty'' (KHM 50), ''The Water Mermaid'' (KHM 79), ''The Golden Key'' (KHM 200), ''Phoenix Bird'' (KHM 75a), ''The Blacksmith and the Devil'' (KHM 81a ), ''Der Froschprinz'' (KHM 99a), the text fragment ''princess with the louse'', and possibly ''Snow White'' (KHM 53).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bottigheimer|first=Ruth B.|date=2006|title=Clever Maids: The Secret History of the Grimm Fairy Tales (review)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1353/mat.2006.0004|journal=Marvels &amp; Tales|volume=20|issue=1|pages=127\u2013129|doi=10.1353/mat.2006.0004|issn=1536-1802}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:German writers]]\n[[Category:Women writers]]\n[[Category:1788 births]]\n[[Category:1856 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name             = Marie Hassenpflug\n| image            = Marie Hassenpflug Bildnis.jpg\n| imagesize        = \n| caption          = Marie Hassenpflug, 1812\n| birth_name       = \n| birth_date       = December 27, 1788\n| birth_place      = Altenha\u00dflau, Germany\n| death_date       = November 21, 1856\n| death_place      = [[Kassel, Germany]]\n| nationality      = \n| spouse           = Friedrich von Dalwigk zu Schauenburg\n| field            = [[Writer]]\n}}\n'''Marie Magdalene Elisabeth Hassenpflug''' (born December 27, 1788 in [[Altenha\u00dflau, Germany,]] \u2020 November 21, 1856 in [[Kassel]]), married ''to Dalwigk von Schaumburg'', was an important source and initial writer of fairy tales for the collection of children's and household tales by the [[Brothers Grimm]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Boehncke, Heiner,|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/856902587|title=Marie Hassenpflug : eine M\u00e4rchenerz\u00e4hlerin der Br\u00fcder Grimm|others=Schmidt, Phoebe Alexa,|isbn=978-3-8053-4536-1|location=Darmstadt|oclc=856902587}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Boehncke|first=Heiner|url=https://searchworks.stanford.edu/view/10238940|title=Marie Hassenpflug : eine M\u00e4rchenerz\u00e4hlerin der Br\u00fcder Grimm /|date=c2013.|publisher=Philipp von Zabern,|isbn=978-3-8053-4536-1|location=Darmstadt :}}</ref> She is most well known for her writings of [[Little Red Riding Hood]], [[Sleeping Beauty]], and [[Snow White]]. \n\n== Life ==\nMarie was the daughter of Johannes Hassenpflug (1755-1834) and Marie Magdalena Dresen (born September 28, 1767 in [[Hanau]], \u2020 December 19, 1840 in [[Kassel]]), who came from a Huguenot emigrant family based in Hanau, and was one sister of the Kurhessian Minister of the Interior and Justice Ludwig Hassenpflug (1794-1862). When her father, Johannes Hassenpflug, became the school hotspot of Hanau Neustadt in 1789, the family moved into an apartment in \"Haus Amsterdam\", later \"Haus Lossow\", a representative half-timbered building on the southwest corner of the market square. The family was friends with the Grimm family, whose father, Philipp Wilhelm Grimm, was the clerk of the city and the B\u00fcchertal office. In 1799 the Hassenpflug family moved to Kassel, where Johannes Hassenpflug had moved to the financial administration of the Landgraviate of Hesse-Kassel.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fr.de/rhein-main/main-kinzig-kreis/spd-org26325/marie-hassenpflug-kind-lebte-11651780.html|title=Wo Marie Hassenpflug als Kind lebte|date=2013-09-06|website=https://www.fr.de|language=de|access-date=2020-04-29}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/681999404|title=Fairy tales and society : illusion, allusion, and paradigm|date=1986|publisher=University of Pennsylvania Press|others=Bottigheimer, Ruth B.,|isbn=978-0-8122-0150-5|location=Philadelphia|oclc=681999404}}</ref>\n\nMarie Hassenpflug married Friedrich von Dalwigk zu Schauenburg on August 21, 1814, who was stationed in Hanau as captain of the ''Kurprinz regiment'' . In the following period she lived on her husband's farm in Hoof (today part of [[Schauenburg]]) and in Hanau. Her son, Ludwig Alexander, was born here on January 24, 1817.\n\nFrom 1819 to 1824 she had a job as [[court lady]] of the Duchess Marie Friederike von Anhalt-Bernburg, a daughter of the landgrave and later Elector Wilhelm IX./I. from Hessen-Kassel. Her husband was also the Duchess' [[Chamberlain (office)|chamberlain]]. During this time they lived in the Hanau City Palace. \n\n== Literary Significance ==\nMarie Hassenpflug wrote a series of fairy tales that the [[Brothers Grimm|Grimm brothers]] portray in the ''children's and house fairy tales'' (KHM) they wrote: ''Little Brother and Sister'' (KHM 11), ''Little Red Riding Hood'' (KHM 26), ''The Girl Without Hands'' (KHM 31), ''The robber groom'' (KHM 40), ''Daumerling's wanderings'' (KHM 45), ''Sleeping Beauty'' (KHM 50), ''The Water Mermaid'' (KHM 79), ''The Golden Key'' (KHM 200), ''Phoenix Bird'' (KHM 75a), ''The Blacksmith and the Devil'' (KHM 81a ), ''Der Froschprinz'' (KHM 99a), the text fragment ''princess with the louse'', and possibly ''Snow White'' (KHM 53).<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bottigheimer|first=Ruth B.|date=2006|title=Clever Maids: The Secret History of the Grimm Fairy Tales (review)|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1353/mat.2006.0004|journal=Marvels &amp; Tales|volume=20|issue=1|pages=127\u2013129|doi=10.1353/mat.2006.0004|issn=1536-1802}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:German writers]]\n[[Category:Women writers]]\n[[Category:1788 births]]\n[[Category:1856 deaths]]\n", "name_user": "Mk170101", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Marie_Hassenpflug"}
